Salary should be classified as Confidentiality: High, Integrity: High, Availability: Medium. Confidentiality is high because salary reveals sensitive compensation information about an identifiable employee and unauthorized disclosure can cause privacy, legal, and workplace harm. Integrity is high because incorrect salary data can lead to underpayment, overpayment, tax/reporting errors, and contractual or regulatory violations. Availability is usually medium because HR/payroll staff need timely access for payroll and compliance, but short outages are typically less damaging than disclosure or tampering. Under GDPR, salary is personal data because it relates to an identified or identifiable natural person. It is generally not a special category of personal data under Article 9, unless it indirectly reveals something special-category-related in context. A practical GDPR label is "personal data, confidential HR/payroll data, elevated sensitivity."
